SIMPLE: slake
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slake
<hw>Slake</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Slaked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Slaking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>slaken</ets> to render
slack, to slake, AS. <ets>sleacian</ets>, fr. <ets>sleac</ets> slack.
See <er>Slack</er>, <pos>v. & a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To allay;
to quench; to extinguish; <as>as, to <ex>slake</ex> thirst</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧And <xex>slake</xex> the heavenly fire.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It could not <qex>slake</qex> mine ire nor ease my heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mix with water, so that a true chemical
combination shall take place; to slack; <as>as, to <ex>slake</ex>
lime</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Slake
<hw>Slake</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To go out; to become
extinct.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His flame did <xex>slake</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir
T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To abate; to become less decided.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To slacken; to become relaxed.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧When the
body's strongest sinews <xex>slake</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir J. Davies.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To become mixed with water, so that a true chemical
combination takes place; <as>as, the lime
<ex>slakes</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Slake trough</b></col>, <cd>a trough containing water in
which a blacksmith cools a forging or tool.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slakeless</ent>⟦br⟧
